I replaced the errno strings with more verbose errors.  Examples:

```
$ curl 127.0.0.1:51343/foo
{
  "request_id": "a088701b-b77e-44dc-937c-b77be9ec76c0",
  "message": "failed to access \"./foo\": No such file or directory (os error 2)"
}

$ curl 127.0.0.1:51343/bar
{
  "request_id": "1698473f-b389-4769-a3c1-900e8952a68f",
  "message": "attempted to follow symlink \"./bar\""
}

$ curl 127.0.0.1:51343/bonk
{
  "request_id": "1be60353-1459-4aca-ac65-4f9d3092d2f3",
  "message": "failed to access \"./bonk\": No such file or directory (os error 2)"
}

$ curl 127.0.0.1:51343/a/b/c
{
  "request_id": "e9d04c0c-b6e0-44d7-98bf-8058fae4f009",
  "message": "failed to access \"./a\": No such file or directory (os error 2)"
}
$ touch foo
$ curl 127.0.0.1:51343/foo/a/b
{
  "request_id": "3a63cfa6-69dd-4041-bfc7-62c221e5580b",
  "message": "expected directory: \"./foo\""
}
```

I also noticed there's kind of a big TOCTOU race in the way we check symlinks.  I think this is usually fixed with the `openat` family of functions.  I'm not sure if Rust exposes those.  Anyway, I didn't want to take that on right now so I've noted it for readers...but it does make me a little uneasy to have this in the example.

This PR makes it so schemas defined with an example (via schemars) are passed-through to the generated OpenAPI JSON.

Currently, specifying an example using schemars will be lost when the OpenAPI JSON is generated by dropshot.  This PR ensures any examples specified are passed along to the resultant JSON.

In the OpenAPI spec (`v3.0.3`) it is possible to specify an `example` key inside most objects (see [spec](https://spec.openapis.org/oas/v3.0.3#model-with-example)). `schemars` has supported examples by using an example function since version `v0.7.6` (see [changelog](https://github.com/GREsau/schemars/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md#076---2020-05-17)).

This PR is completely "opt-in" - if a user does not specify an example then their generated JSON should look the same as it has before this PR.

---

To specify an example you need to tell schemars how to find the function that generates an example struct:

``` rust
#[derive(Deserialize, Serialize, JsonSchema)]
#[schemars(example = "example_student")]
struct Student {
    id: u32,
    name: String,
}

fn example_student() -> Student {
    Student {
        id: 1,
        name: "Foo Bar".into(),
    }
}
```

The schema created for `Student` will look something like:

``` json
{
  "Student": {
    "example": {
      "id": 1,
      "name": "Foo Bar",
    },
    "type": "object"
  }
}
```

(truncated for this example)

---

An example of this is included in this PR in the `example.rs`:

    $ cargo run -q --example example | jq .components.schemas.Foo
    {
      "example": {
        "bar": {
          "id": 2
        },
        "id": 1
      },
      "title": "Foo Object",
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
      ...

---

This code passes:

    cargo check
    cargo clippy
    cargo fmt

And both of these work (and pass) as expected:

    cargo run --example example
    cargo test --test test_openapi

For crucible and the update system, it's useful to be able to respond with a freeform body. Dropshot allows this today, but doing so removes both the expected status code and structural information about errors. This introduces a endpoint response type:

```rust
async fn stream_bytes_at_me_please(
    rqctx: Arc<RequestContext<()>>,
) -> Result<HttpResponseOk<FreeformBody>, HttpError> {
    let (sender, body) = Body::channel();
    // spawn a task to spew bytes into `sender`
    Ok(HttpResponseOk(body.into()))
}
```

Note this involves some reshuffling of types--I think--for the better. For example, `Empty` no longer `impl`s `Serialize` or `JsonSchema` and the numeric response code trait is separated from the content trait.

If a consumer specifies an endpoint whose return type is `Result<http::Response<hyper::Body>, HttpError>` we would generate OpenAPI like this:

```json
"responses": {}
```

This isn't valid OpenAPI 3.0.3:

> The Responses Object MUST contain at least one response code, and it SHOULD be the response for a successful operation call.
https://github.com/OAI/OpenAPI-Specification/blob/main/versions/3.0.3.md#responses-object

This PR changes the output to this:

```json
"responses": {
  "default": {
    "description": ""
  }
}
```

It's not a **lot** better, but at least it satisfied the `swagger-cli` tool. This PR also adds the execution of that tool to make sure the output of `test_openapi` is valid.
